Task 1: Selecting the best

In this task, we will be looking at survey data for high school students. The survey includes demographic and socioeconomic information, in addition to social and study variables.

students <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/maibennett/sta235/main/exampleSite/content/Assignments/Homework/data/hw5/student.csv")

You can see a codebook of the variables here

First, we will transform all character variables into factors, so we consider them now as categorical variables:

students <- students %>% mutate_if(is.character, as.factor)

We will also do the same with numeric variables that should be considered categorical:

students <- students %>% mutate(across(c(Medu, Fedu, traveltime, studytime),
                                       as.factor))

Our goal is to best predict the final grade of a student given their characteristics.

Question 1.2

Let’s first use our trusty OLS model. Fit a regression with every covariate we have available using 10-fold cross validation, but make sure to exclude school and first and second period grade from the analysis (we will not use them as predictors). How does it perform in terms of RMSE? Interpret your accuracy measure in terms of the mean of the outcome. (Note: Train your model only on your previously created training dataset)

Answer: Using this model, we can see that the RMSE is 2.7, which means that the average error for our prediction model is 2.7 points in the final grade. This represents 22% of the average final grade in our testing sample, so we could say it’s a substantial error.


set.seed(100)

# Fit a linear model

Answer: Compared to our previous model, our new model is using only 40 out of the 48 covariates. This model does perform slightly better, with a RMSE of 2.69, but it’s not a substantial improvement. Either way, using the RMSE as our measure, we would choose this new subsetted model instead of the previous full linear model.


set.seed(100)

# Fit a forward stepwise selection model

Question 1.4

Now use a Lasso approach to create a new model. (a) What is the optimal penalty term? (show the results and an appropriate plot), (b) How does this model compare to the previous ones?, and (c) which one would you prefer out of the three models you have tested so far?

Answer: First, we fit a lasso regression using the caret package and glmnet (we are sure to change \(\alpha\) to 1)


set.seed(100)

# This lambda_seq was created after doing a first pass with a more general vector
lambda_seq <- seq(0,2, by = 0.001)

# Fit a lasso model
lasso_model <- train(G3 ~ . - G1 - G2 - school, data = train.data,
                  method = "glmnet",
                  preProcess = "scale",
                  trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10),
                  tuneGrid = expand.grid(alpha = 1, 
                         lambda = lambda_seq))

Looking at the plot below, we see that the penalty term is close to 0, but is not exactly 0. In fact, the optimal lambda in this case is \(\lambda = 0.065\).


# Create a dataframe for the plot
cv_lambda <- data.frame(lambda = lasso_model$results$lambda,
                        rmse = lasso_model$results$RMSE)

ggplot(data = cv_lambda, aes(x = lambda, y = rmse)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = "#BF3984"), lwd = 1.2) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = lasso_model$bestTune$lambda, color = "dark grey"), lty=2, lwd = 1.1) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("#BF3984","dark grey"),
                     labels = c("#BF3984" = "CV-RMSE","dark grey" = "Min \u03BB"),
                     name = "") + theme_bw()+
  xlab("\u03BB") + ylab("RMSE")

Comparing it to our previous model, lasso selects fewer variables compared to forward stepwise subsetting (36 vs 40), and of course that’s less than the full model with 48 covariates. In terms of RMSE, this is the model that performs the best so far, with a RMSE of 2.67, which is just under 22% of the average outcome in the testing dataset.


# Show best model
coef(lasso_model$finalModel, lasso_model$bestTune$lambda)

# How many covariates?
length(coef(lasso_model$finalModel, lasso_model$bestTune$lambda)@x)-1

# Obtain the RMSE
rmse(lasso_model, test.data)

rmse(lasso_model, test.data)/mean_outcome

Question 1.5

Comment on why do you think Lasso should outperform stepwise subsetting in terms of model selection.

Answer: Lasso in this case has an advantage over stepwise subsetting because it’s also doing model selection (selecting a subset of predictors), but, at the same time, is adding an optimal penalty term for reducing variance (but increasing bias). The optimal term is selected so that the reduction in variance is more than the increase in bias, so that, overall, we are gaining accuracy. Stepwise, on the other hand, doesn’t provide the additional gain in accuracy by reducing variance and is usually not optimal because it doesn’t test all models


  • 100%: Correctly mentions that stepwise is not optimal because it doesn’t test all possible models. It could also mention that lasso is doing model selection and adding bias to reduce variance, unlike stepwise, which is only doing model selection.

  • 80%: Provides a comprehensive description of both methods, but doesn’t actually explicitly compare them.

  • 50%: Describes some of the properties of lasso and stepwise, but doesn’t do a proper comparison.

  • 20%: Attempts something that has some meaning, but overall incorrect.

  • 0%: Any other case.

Question 3.3

Let’s start with the basics. Using a logistic regression and all the predictors in your dataset, test the performance of this model by predicting the probability of unsubscribing. Assign any customer with a prediction higher than .5 a value of 1 in the predicted outcome and 0 otherwise. What is the accuracy of your model? (Note: remember to use the right datasets for training your model and testing; no need to use cross-validation in this case).

Answer: First, we fit a logit model with everything, but we exclude the id variable (we can do this directly in the code, or remove it from the dataset). After training our model in the train data, we predict the probability of unsubscribing, and create a new variable that takes the value of 1 if the probability is greater that 0.5. We can see that the accuracy for this model (on the testing dataset) is 76%.


logit <- glm(Churn ~ ., data = train.data %>% select(-customerID), 
             family = binomial(link = "logit"))

prob_l <- logit %>% predict(., test.data, type = "response")

test.data <- test.data %>% mutate(pred_logit = ifelse(prob_l>0.5,1,0))

test.data %>% select(Churn, pred_logit) %>% table %>% proportions(., margin = 1) %>% round(.,3)

mean(test.data$Churn==test.data$pred_logit)

Identify those individuals that you incorrectly categorized as unsubscribers (1) in your KNN model, and compare them in terms of their characteristics to the actual unsubscribers in your testing dataset. Do they look alike in terms of their characteristics? Comment on a couple of potential differences or similarities. (Note: Use gender, senior citizen, partner, dependents, tenure, contract, and monthly charges. Make the appropriate transformations to your data to assess statistically whether they are similar or not)

Answer: We can see from our balance table below, that there are some differences in terms of characteristics. For example, actual unsubscribers have been longer with the company, compared to the wrongly classified, and they are more likely to have dependents.

# Select the variables we need, and transform string variables into numeric.
test.data.bal <- test.data %>% select(pred_knn, Churn, gender, SeniorCitizen, Partner,
                                      Dependents, tenure, Contract, MonthlyCharges) %>%
  mutate(female = as.numeric(factor(gender))-1,
         Partner = as.numeric(factor(Partner)) - 1,
         Dependents = as.numeric(factor(Dependents)) - 1,
         Contract.month = ifelse(Contract=="Month-to-month",1,0),
         Contract.1year = ifelse(Contract=="One year", 1, 0),
         Contract.2year = ifelse(Contract=="Two year", 1, 0)) %>% 
  select(-c(gender, Contract))

#Create a variable that is 1 if is an unsubscriber in the observed data
test.data.bal <- test.data.bal %>% mutate(comparison = ifelse(pred_knn!=Churn & Churn==0,
                                                              "Wrong Churn", ifelse(Churn==1,"Obs Churn",NA))) %>%
  select(-c(pred_knn, Churn))

datasummary_balance(~ comparison, data = test.data.bal, stars = TRUE, fmt = 2,
                    dinm_statistic = "p.value")
